explanation: - OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: The macro expansion determines how the second argument (*token) is used. It could perform assignments or take the address of its argument; we must inspect the macro to see if it modifies the parameter variable 'token' (or attempts to assign to the expression passed). - OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: The macro likely calls this helper. Its prototype/definition shows whether it takes the token by value or by pointer and whether it modifies the object or attempts to modify the caller's parameter. This is necessary to determine if any modification to the parameter (or the pointed object) occurs. - OS_object_token_t: The exact type (and const qualification semantics) is needed to know what *token denotes (is it an lvalue, is it const-qualified?) and whether writes through that expression would attempt to modify the object or violate const rules. - OS_impl_count_sem_table: The macro may reference or index this table; its type/definition can show how the macro uses the token argument (e.g., as an index, as an lvalue), which bears on whether the parameter is modified. - OS_impl_countsem_internal_record_t: Knowing the record type confirms that the impl assignment and subsequent use (impl->id) do not involve modifying the function parameter. It helps rule out indirect modifications via side effects inside the returned record or table access.
